December loth, 1851.—1n latitude 270 04’ North, longitude 790 44’ West, a sounding was got with 380 sathoms line; time of running, 4 minutes 51 secondS. Temp. air 740, temp. water 800.

The same day having changed our latitude to 270 16’ North, longitude 790 49’ West, we repeated the experiment, and got bottom with 274 fathoms line ; time of running, 3 minutes 24 seconds. Having made up my mind to get several casts across the Florida stream, so as to make sure of the greatest depth at this part of its course3 I was very much disappointed in finding myself upon the western side of the channel, as the soundings proved conclusively.

The wind was too light to enable me to get back into the middle part of the stream, and 1 was reluct- antly compelled to relinquish my design.

The error in our position can be easily accounted for, by the fact that we were from 6 P. M. of the 8th, beating about in this narrow pass and rapid stream, without observationS, or being able to get hold of any landmark.
